{|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image= |Ship caption= }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship country=[[Dutch Republic]] |Ship flag=[[File:Statenvlag.svg|60px]] |Ship name= '''''The Flying Deer''''' |Ship namesake= |Ship owner= |Ship operator= |Ship registry= |Ship route= |Ship ordered= |Ship awarded= |Ship builder= |Ship original cost= |Ship yard number= |Ship way number= |Ship laid down= |Ship launched= |Ship sponsor= |Ship christened= |Ship completed= |Ship acquired= |Ship commissioned= |Ship recommissioned= |Ship decommissioned= |Ship maiden voyage= |Ship in service= |Ship out of service= |Ship renamed= |Ship reclassified= |Ship refit= |Ship struck= |Ship reinstated= |Ship homeport= |Ship identification= |Ship motto= |Ship nickname= |Ship honours= |Ship honors= |Ship captured= |Ship fate=Lost with all hands in August 1638 |Ship status= |Ship notes= |Ship badge= }} |} '''''The''''' '''''Flying Deer''''' ([[Dutch language|dutch]]: '''''Het fliegende hert''''') was a 17th century [[Dutch Empire|Dutch]] ship. She was lost at sea with all hands during a hurricane off [[St. kitts|St. Kitts]] in 1638.
== History == '''''The Flying Deer''''' was an early 17th century [[sloop]] in dutch service. She was recorded as participating in the lucrative trans-Atlantic [[tobacco]] trade. In August 1638, the sloop was anchored off island of St. Kitts when the [[Sweden|Swedish]]-flagged [[Kalmar Nyckel|''Kalmar Nykle'']] (which was returning from its first voyage to establish [[New Sweden]]) also dropped anchor off the island.<ref>''The Kalmar Nykle''; A Guide to the Ship and Her History. The Kalmar Nykle Foundation, Wilmington D.E.
URL: http://www.kalmarnyckel.org/docs/knf_guidebook.pdf</ref> The captain of ''The'' ''Flying Deer'' was a friend of [[Peter Minuit]], a prominent explorer aboard the Swedish ship, and so Minuit and Captain [[Jan Hindricksen van der Water]] of ''Kalmar Nykle'' were invited aboard ''The Flying Deer''. During the visit, a powerful storm (possibly a [[Tropical cyclone|hurricane]]) swept up on the island, battering the ships at anchor. ''Kalmar Nykle'' rode out the storm at sea, but ''The Flying Deer'' was never seen again and presumed to be lost with all hands.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9wd5AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA41&lpg=PA41&dq=dutch+ship+flying+deer&source=bl&ots=qSKkKHDReM&sig=c6MvDpr3NF_uaBror9orcOc_jCM&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi52aqEr8_bAhXR1lMKHWTsArwQ6AEINzAG#v=onepage&q=dutch%20ship%20flying%20deer&f=false|title=General history|last=Scharf|first=John Thomas|date=1888|publisher=L. J. Richards & Company|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z3VKAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA47&lpg=PA47&dq=dutch+ship+flying+deer&source=bl&ots=wOtuaHNMTs&sig=R8fCT-n5mwl8krgjFfOHsTgdNWs&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi52aqEr8_bAhXR1lMKHWTsArwQ6AEIVTAJ#v=onepage&q=dutch%20ship%20flying%20deer&f=false|title=A History of the Swedish-Americans of Minnesota|last=Strand|first=Algot E.|date=1910|publisher=Lewis Publishing|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Qh4UAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA65&lpg=PA65&dq=dutch+ship+flying+deer&source=bl&ots=aRACcJ68pz&sig=3RRzliAf3hE_BTFz0lkGIyuhYWQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi52aqEr8_bAhXR1lMKHWTsArwQ6AEIVzAK#v=onepage&q=dutch%20ship%20flying%20deer&f=false|title=History of Philadelphia|last=Scharf|first=T.|publisher=Рипол Классик|isbn=9785883517104|language=en}}</ref>
